<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/14206112-gary-jannarone"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1351909377i/14206112._UY100_CR32,0,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/14206112-gary-jannarone">Gary Jannarone</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">I&apos;m half-way through the book. There is a different perspective as to the reasons for the Civil War, aka, The War of Northern Aggression, which is exp<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">I'm half-way through the book. There is a different perspective as to the reasons for the Civil War, aka, The War of Northern Aggression, which is explained in this book. I find it revealing to examine the causes of the war cleansed of 21st century mores. If you limit yourself to the prevailing values and conditions of the first half of the 19th century you may see things in a different light. I always used to cheer for the Union, but now I don't see it as being so one-sided when considering who held the high moral ground.<br />But mainly, it is a very interesting biography.<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
