<div id="review_3466952961" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3466952961" />
    <a title="Thomas Achord" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/27266416-thomas-achord"><img alt="Thomas Achord" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1499341760p2/27266416.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3466952961?book_show_action=true">Jul 28, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Thomas Achord" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Thomas Achord" href="/user/show/27266416-thomas-achord">Thomas Achord</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/27266416-thomas-achord?shelf=biography">biography</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3466952961" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5518956533578567853">The reviews of this book are more about Jackson or the war than the book itself. They complain Jackson was too violent. What would they have to say about northern generals who wen ton to practice total war? They betray lack of depth, implying they didn&apos;t actually read the book. True historians do not speak in tweetable quips. <br/><br/>Jackson was a man dedicated to his duty to God and superiors. He seemed less patriotic than religious, less grand-scheming than direct-strategizing. This made him deadly on</span>
  <span id="freeText5518956533578567853" style="display:none">The reviews of this book are more about Jackson or the war than the book itself. They complain Jackson was too violent. What would they have to say about northern generals who wen ton to practice total war? They betray lack of depth, implying they didn't actually read the book. True historians do not speak in tweetable quips. <br /><br />Jackson was a man dedicated to his duty to God and superiors. He seemed less patriotic than religious, less grand-scheming than direct-strategizing. This made him deadly on a field of battle with generals more concerned about reputation and posturing. Jackson's faults emerged in peacetime, as his character came alive in war. He couldn't keep a class of students together but he could order and lead men on the battlefield like few others in history. His trust in God's providence gave him the interior calm amid a storm of bullets and agony. </span>
  <a data-text-id="5518956533578567853" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


