<div id="review_2850554846" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2850554846" />
    <a title="Katedurie50" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/96640374-katedurie50"><img alt="Katedurie50" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2850554846?book_show_action=true">Jun 11, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Katedurie50" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Katedurie50" href="/user/show/96640374-katedurie50">Katedurie50</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2850554846" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4845166401436602723">This is more than a biography of Stonewall Jackson. It&apos;s also a snapshot of much of the war and its conditions - skirmishes and pitched battles; largely untrained soldiers having to be formed (or drifting away or deserting)into fighting units; exhaustion; bloody carnage and disease; hunger and the importance of supply trains (victory over a fleeing Union army could mean the capture of better food as well as weapons). But there is no doubting the man&apos;s dominance; when Stonewall was shot, Lee comm</span>
  <span id="freeText4845166401436602723" style="display:none">This is more than a biography of Stonewall Jackson. It's also a snapshot of much of the war and its conditions - skirmishes and pitched battles; largely untrained soldiers having to be formed (or drifting away or deserting)into fighting units; exhaustion; bloody carnage and disease; hunger and the importance of supply trains (victory over a fleeing Union army could mean the capture of better food as well as weapons). But there is no doubting the man's dominance; when Stonewall was shot, Lee commented that Jackson had lost his left arm but Lee himself had thus lost his right arm. They made a formidable team. I'm struck by how much Jackson was made by the war; before it an ungainly, eccentric professor, but in battle an inspired tactician and leader of men, by whom he was adored. By his death, the adulation was widely shared in the South and his funeral has resonance with that of Lincoln and perhaps, later, Kennedy. It is telling, too, how much respect he garnered on the Union side.<br />The man was a mass of contradictions. Capable of kindness, gentleness and compassion, he was utterly inflexible where duty was concerned, expecting his officers and men to bear hardship as he did; he had a regrettable habit of court-martialling subordinates. For all his daring and dazzling success, there was an interlude where he seems to have failed in body and mind. His religious faith and principle are central, but the idea that his God might not be entirely on the side of the confederacy never occured to him. He was modest, reticent, privately affectionate, often awkward in company, embarrassed by admirers (especially women), keen on Shakespeare and English cathedrals, obsessed with entire obedience to regulations, and lived on a self-imposed diet of little more than stale bread and occasional peaches. He was so famous that a Union prisoner was found stealing hairs from the tail of Little Sorrel, Jackson's horse; when Jackson mildly asked why, the man replied that each hair would fetch a dollar in New York. This book helps us understand why.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4845166401436602723" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


