    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2414029991" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2414029991" />
    <a title="Alex" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2057817-alex"><img alt="Alex" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1240861622p2/2057817.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2414029991?book_show_action=true">Jun 22, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Alex" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Alex" href="/user/show/2057817-alex">Alex</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2414029991" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13161802902502870016">This is extremely good. Well written, too. It is not easy to describe battles in detail without making it mind-numbing, but Gwynne does it. He shows well how Jackson was fighting battles and organizing campaigns in ways that were simply on a different level than his adversaries. Had Jackson not died, the Federals would have still won the war—the North’s material advantages were just too large, particularly once Grant started marshaling them all; it was only a matter of time—but Jackson’s death w</span>
  <span id="freeText13161802902502870016" style="display:none">This is extremely good. Well written, too. It is not easy to describe battles in detail without making it mind-numbing, but Gwynne does it. He shows well how Jackson was fighting battles and organizing campaigns in ways that were simply on a different level than his adversaries. Had Jackson not died, the Federals would have still won the war—the North’s material advantages were just too large, particularly once Grant started marshaling them all; it was only a matter of time—but Jackson’s death was probably the war’s most important turning point in the Eastern theatre. <br /><br />Jackson may have been the most pious American alive in the 1850s and early 60s. I’m hardly exaggerating. He prayed continually. About everything. His letters read like devotions. Gwynne treats this fairly. Frankly, that aspect of Jackson’s life seems, as Gwynne tells it, as unique as Jackson’s military career. <br /><br />In the 1850s, while employed as a professor at VMI, Jackson started the first Sunday School in the Shenandoah Valley for blacks. When informed by town leaders that he was breaking the law (based on a Virginia statute that forbade teaching slaves how to read), he refused to shut down his Sunday school, which was attended by more than 100 local slaves and freedmen at a time, and thus risked criminal prosecution and his job. On multiple occasions during the 1850s, local slaves asked Jackson to purchase them so that he could then emancipate them. Which he did. <br /><br />I understand why people feel compelled to tear down statues of CSA leaders. But, I don’t think it is deserved for Jackson. </span>
  <a data-text-id="13161802902502870016" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


